{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2002 |Team=Penn State Nittany Lions |Image= |ImageSize= |Conference=Big Ten Conference |ShortConference=Big Ten |Division= |CoachRank=15 |APRank=16 |Record=9â4 |ConfRecord=5â3 |HeadCoach=[[Joe Paterno]] |OffCoach=Fran Ganter |DefCoach=[[Tom Bradley (American football)|Tom Bradley]] |OScheme= |DScheme= |StadiumArena=[[Beaver Stadium]] |Champion= |BowlTourney={{Alternate links|2003 Capital One Bowl|Capital One Bowl|title=Capital One Bowl}} |BowlTourneyResult=L 13â9 vs. [[2002 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] }} {{2002 Big Ten football standings}} The '''2002 Penn State Nittany Lions football team''' represented the [[Pennsylvania State University]] in the [[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002â2003 college football season]]. The team's head coach was [[Joe Paterno]]. It played its home games at [[Beaver Stadium]] in [[University Park, Pennsylvania]].
==Preseason== The Nittany Lions returned 16 starters from the previous season, who won five of its final seven games. Six starters returned on defense, led by defensive tackle [[Jimmy Kennedy (American football)|Jimmy Kennedy]], who returned for his fifth year despite speculations he would enter the [[NFL Draft]].<ref name="kennedydraft">{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011002aaa.html|title=Kennedy To Return For Senior Season|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics|date=2002-01-10|accessdate=2007-01-23}}</ref>
The offensive unit averted a possible quarterback controversy when last year's starter [[Matt Senneca]] announced that he would not be returning for his final year of eligibility.<ref name="senneca">{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011602aaa.html|title=Matt Senneca Not Returning for Senior Season|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics|date=2002-01-16|accessdate=2007-01-23}}</ref> Redshirt sophomore [[Zack Mills]] would lead the offense, with expectations high after showing flashes of brilliance coming off the bench in 2001. [[Larry Johnson (American football)|Larry Johnson]] would also become the featured back, after spending three seasons playing in a tailback-by-committee that had inconsistent production. Johnson will have the luxury of running behind an offensive line that returned all five starters.
Penn State was ranked number 24 in both the [[Associated Press|AP]] and [[Coaches Poll|Coaches]] college football preseason polls.
