The [[2002 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Buckeyes]] defense held [[Zack Mills]] to only 98 yards passing and intercepted three passes, including one by [[Chris Gamble]] returned for a touchdown, to beat the Nittany Lions 13â7. Penn State was held to only 179 yards of offense and eight first downs, fewest under [[Joe Paterno]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/102602aaa.html|title=Nittany Lions Fall 13â7 to Buckeyes in Defensive Dogfight|date=2002-10-26|accessdate=2008-10-28|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics}}</ref> Despite this, Penn State led 7â3 at halftime and very nearly won the game at the end.
