==Post season==
Penn State finished the season ranked #16 in the final [[Associated Press|AP]] college football poll and #15 in the final [[Coaches Poll|Coaches]] college football poll, earning Penn State its 25th Top 15 finish under Joe Paterno.<ref name="rankings">{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/010403aaa.html|title=Nittany Lions Earn 25th Top 15 Final Ranking Under Paterno|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics|date=2003-01-04|accessdate=2007-01-23}}</ref>
Tailback [[Larry Johnson (American football)|Larry Johnson]] would finish the season as the first Nittany Lion to lead the nation in rushing and all-purpose yardage. Johnson become the ninth player in Division I-A history to gain 2,000 yards rushing in the regular season, finishing third in [[Heisman Trophy]] balloting.<ref name="johnson">{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011603aaa.html|title=Larry Johnson Is First Nittany Lion to Lead Nation in Rushing & All-Purpose Yardage; Haynes Among NCAA Defensive Leaders|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics|date=2003-01-16|accessdate=2007-01-23}}</ref>
Penn State claimed second place in football attendance for the second consecutive season, averaging 107,239 through eight home games, ranking in the top four for the 12th consecutive year. The Nittany Lions also broke the NCAA record for total season attendance with 1,247,707 during the 13-game schedule, including a Beaver Stadium record of 110,753 for the Nebraska game.<ref name="attendance">{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/021003aaa.html|title=Penn State Claims Second In NCAA Football Attendance; Breaks NCAA Record For Total Attendance with 1.2 Million Fans|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics|date=2003-02-10|accessdate=2007-01-23}}</ref>
===NFL draft=== A school record six seniors would be drafted in the first two rounds of the [[2003 NFL Draft]], including another school record four players in the first round.<ref name="draft">{{cite web|url=http://gopsusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/042803aaa.html|title=Nittany Lions Lead All Schools With Six Selections in First Two Rounds of NFL Draft|publisher=Penn State Intercollegiate Athletics|date=2003-04-28|accessdate=2007-01-23}}</ref>
